---
import HomeBase from "../../layouts/HomeBase.astro";
import SiteFooter from "../../components/sections/SiteFooter.astro";
import SiteHeader from "../../components/sections/SiteHeader.astro";
import home from "../../content/home.json";

const description = "How 22 Strong Foundation handles money, care, trust, and its provider relationship.";
---

<HomeBase title="How we handle money, care, and trust" description={description}>
  <div class="site site--about">
    <SiteHeader current="transparency" />

    <main id="main" class="about-page transparency-page">
      <section class="transparency-hero" aria-labelledby="transparency-title">
        <div class="transparency-hero__inner">
          <p class="eyebrow">Transparency</p>
          <h1 id="transparency-title">How we handle money, care, and trust</h1>
          <p class="lead">
            22 Strong Foundation is a 501(c)(3) nonprofit. We fund recovery care for veterans
            and low-income youth when their coverage runs out. Because of how this organization
            started, we want to be straight with you about how it is built and how money moves.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <div class="transparency-copy">
        <section class="transparency-section" aria-labelledby="where-started">
          <h2 id="where-started">Where we started, and why it matters</h2>
          <p>
            22 Strong grew out of Next Level Fitness & Wellness Center, a sports-medicine clinic
            in Newport Beach. Two of the people who lead the foundation, Dr. Vasili Gatsinaris
            and Travis Mayfield, co-own that clinic. Right now, the recovery care we fund is
            provided there.
          </p>
          <p>
            That means your donation can pay for care at a clinic our founders have a financial
            stake in. We do not hide that relationship or make you find it in fine print. We name
            it on the care pathway, we explain it here, and we keep the foundation's role narrow:
            22 Strong funds approved recovery care for people whose next appointment is at risk.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="transparency-section" aria-labelledby="what-money-funds">
          <h2 id="what-money-funds">What your donation pays for</h2>
          <p>
            22 Strong pays for hands-on recovery sessions for veterans and low-income youth when
            coverage, timing, or cost puts care out of reach. A recovery session is listed at
            $190. The person receiving care does not receive cash from 22 Strong.
          </p>
          <ul class="transparency-list transparency-list--checks">
            <li>Funds are tied to approved recovery care, not unrestricted clinic revenue.</li>
            <li>The care recipient is not billed for the funded session.</li>
            <li>The foundation does not provide emergency care, diagnosis, insurance advice, or direct cash payments.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="transparency-section" aria-labelledby="funding-decision">
          <h2 id="funding-decision">How a funding decision gets made</h2>
          <p>
            A referral or request starts the process. 22 Strong reviews whether an access gap is
            present: insurance has run out, VA timing does not meet the need, or private care is
            out of reach. If the case fits the mission, donor funding covers the recovery care so
            treatment can continue.
          </p>
          <p>
            The provider relationship is treated as a related-party relationship every time it
            matters. A 22 Strong leader with a financial interest in Next Level is expected to
            disclose that interest and step back from approving a decision that would personally
            benefit them.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="transparency-section" aria-labelledby="provider-relationship">
          <h2 id="provider-relationship">Why care currently runs through Next Level</h2>
          <p>
            The foundation began because Dr. Gatsinaris and Mr. Mayfield were seeing the same gap
            inside the treatment room: people were improving, but the next appointment was not
            always covered or affordable. 22 Strong was built to keep that recovery from stopping.
          </p>
          <p>
            Today, all funded care runs through Next Level Fitness & Wellness Center in Newport
            Beach. As 22 Strong grows, this page should grow with it: provider relationships,
            session rates, and review practices should stay visible to donors and referral
            partners.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="transparency-section" aria-labelledby="records">
          <h2 id="records">What you can check or ask</h2>
          <ul class="transparency-list">
            <li>22 Strong Foundation is a 501(c)(3) nonprofit.</li>
            <li>EIN: 99-1232582.</li>
            <li>Questions about the provider relationship, funded care, or giving: <a href="/#contact">contact us</a>.</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="transparency-legal">22 Strong Foundation. 501(c)(3). EIN 99-1232582. Donations are tax-deductible.</p>
        </section>
      </div>

      <section class="transparency-policy" aria-labelledby="policy-title">
        <div class="transparency-policy__inner">
          <p class="eyebrow">Conflict standard</p>
          <h2 id="policy-title">How we manage the Next Level relationship</h2>

          <h3>We say the conflict out loud</h3>
          <p>
            22 Strong funds care at a clinic two of its leaders co-own. That is the conflict. It
            is named here because donors, referral partners, and the people receiving care should
            not have to guess how the model works.
          </p>

          <h3>We keep the nonprofit role narrow</h3>
          <p>
            22 Strong is a funder of approved recovery care. It does not diagnose injuries, sell
            insurance advice, provide emergency medical care, or hand cash to individuals.
          </p>

          <h3>We separate personal interest from approval</h3>
          <p>
            If a 22 Strong decision could personally benefit a director, officer, family member,
            or business they have a stake in, that interest has to be disclosed before the
            decision is made. A person with that conflict should not be the one approving the
            benefit to themselves or their business.
          </p>

          <h3>We keep the care recordable</h3>
          <p>
            Funded support should connect back to a referred person, an access gap, a recovery
            session, and the stated session amount. That is what lets a donor understand what
            their money made possible.
          </p>

          <h3>We keep updating this page</h3>
          <p>
            If 22 Strong adds providers, changes the session amount, or formalizes additional
            review steps, those changes belong here. The standard is simple: the relationship
            should stay visible before a donor has to ask.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>
    </main>

    <SiteFooter footer={home.footer} homeHrefPrefix="/" />
  </div>
</HomeBase>
